<TITLE> Egypt military court delays Brotherhood verdict </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 CAIRO, Feb 26 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - An Egyptian military court delayed on Tuesday issuing a verdict for 40 members of the opposition Muslim Brotherhood on trial over watered-down charges including belonging to a banned group, a Brotherhood lawyer said. Lawyer Abdel Moniem Abdel Maqsoud told Reuters the court set March 25 as the new date for a verdict for the men, who include the Brotherhood's third-in-command Khairat el-Shatir. The group of men, six of whom are being tried in absentia, became the first Brotherhood members to face military trials since 2001 after being referred to a military court a year ago. Most of the serious charges initially levied against the men, including terrorism and money laundering, were reported to have been dropped in December. But the men were still accused of belonging to a banned group and possessing anti-government literature. Local and international rights groups including Amnesty International have criticised the military trial as unfair. Egypt has barred independent observers from the court. The non-violent Muslim Brotherhood, which holds a fifth of the seats in Egypt's parliament, seeks an Islamic state through democratic means and operates openly despite a decades-old ban. The government often detains Brotherhood members without char
